  50 # pylint: disable=line-too-long
  51 # TODO(josh11b): Should device values be strings or DeviceSpec objects?
  52 # Not sure DeviceSpec objects are usable as a dict key.
  53 class DistributedValues(object):
  54   """Holds a map from device to values. Either PerDevice or Mirrored."""
  55 
  56   def __init__(self, index):
  57     self._index = {device_util.canonicalize(key): value
  58                    for key, value in six.iteritems(index)}
  59 
  60   def get(self, device=None):
  61     """Returns the value for the current device or raises a ValueError."""
  62     if device is None:
  63       tower_context = distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context()
  64       if tower_context:
  65         device = tower_context.device
  66       else:
  67         device = distribute_lib.get_update_device()
  68         if device is None:
  69           return self._get_cross_tower()
  70     device = device_util.canonicalize(device)
  71     try:
  72       return self._index[device]
  73     except KeyError as e:
  74       six.raise_from(
  75           ValueError("Device %s not found in %s (current device %s)" %
  76                      (device, self._index.keys(), device_util.current())), e)
  77 
  78   def on_device(self, device):
  79     device = device_util.canonicalize(device)
  80     return device in self._index
  81 
  82   @property
  83   def devices(self):
  84     return list(self._index.keys())
  85 
  86   @property
  87   def is_tensor_like(self):
  88     for v in self._index.values():
  89       if not tensor_util.is_tensor(v):
  90         return False
  91     return True
  92 
  93   def __str__(self):
  94     return "%s:%s" % (self.__class__.__name__, self._index)
  95 
  96   def __repr__(self):
  97     return "%s(%r)" % (self.__class__.__name__, self._index)
  98 
  99   # TODO(josh11b): Possibly make an accessor for _index for use by
 100   # DistributionStrategy implementations.
 101 
 102 
 103 class DistributedDelegate(DistributedValues):
 104   """A map from device to values; acts as the same type as the values."""
 105 
 106   def __init__(self, index):
 107     super(DistributedDelegate, self).__init__(index)
 108 
 109   def __getattr__(self, name):
 110     return getattr(self.get(), name)
 111 
 112   # pylint: disable=multiple-statements
 113   def __add__(self, o): return self.get() + o
 114   def __radd__(self, o): return o + self.get()
 115   def __sub__(self, o): return self.get() - o
 116   def __rsub__(self, o): return o - self.get()
 117   def __mul__(self, o): return self.get() * o
 118   def __rmul__(self, o): return o * self.get()
 119   def __truediv__(self, o): return self.get() / o
 120   def __rtruediv__(self, o): return o / self.get()
 121   def __floordiv__(self, o): return self.get() // o
 122   def __rfloordiv__(self, o): return o // self.get()
 123   def __mod__(self, o): return self.get() % o
 124   def __rmod__(self, o): return o % self.get()
 125   def __lt__(self, o): return self.get() < o
 126   def __le__(self, o): return self.get() <= o
 127   def __gt__(self, o): return self.get() > o
 128   def __ge__(self, o): return self.get() >= o
 129   def __and__(self, o): return self.get() & o
 130   def __rand__(self, o): return o & self.get()
 131   def __or__(self, o): return self.get() | o
 132   def __ror__(self, o): return o | self.get()
 133   def __xor__(self, o): return self.get() ^ o
 134   def __rxor__(self, o): return o ^ self.get()
 135   def __getitem__(self, o): return self.get()[o]
 136   def __pow__(self, o, modulo=None): return pow(self.get(), o, modulo)
 137   def __rpow__(self, o): return pow(o, self.get())
 138   def __invert__(self): return ~self.get()
 139   def __neg__(self): return -self.get()
 140   def __abs__(self): return abs(self.get())
 141 
 142   def __div__(self, o):
 143     try:
 144       return self.get().__div__(o)
 145     except AttributeError:
 146       # See https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
 147       return NotImplemented
 148 
 149   def __rdiv__(self, o):
 150     try:
 151       return self.get().__rdiv__(o)
 152     except AttributeError:
 153       # See https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
 154       return NotImplemented
 155 
 156   def __matmul__(self, o):
 157     try:
 158       return self.get().__matmul__(o)
 159     except AttributeError:
 160       # See https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
 161       return NotImplemented
 162 
 163   def __rmatmul__(self, o):
 164     try:
 165       return self.get().__rmatmul__(o)
 166     except AttributeError:
 167       # See https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
 168       return NotImplemented
 169 
 170   # TODO(josh11b): Even more operator overloads.

 173 class PerDevice(DistributedValues):
 174   """Holds a map from device to unsynchronized values."""
 175   pass

 178 # Note that unlike PerDevice, Mirrored values inherit from
 179 # DistributedDelegate and so can be used directly in cross-tower mode.
 180 class Mirrored(DistributedDelegate):
 181   """Holds a map from device to values which are kept in sync."""
 182 
 183   def _get_cross_tower(self):
 184     device = device_util.canonicalize(device_util.current())
 185     if device in self._index:
 186       return self._index[device]
 187     return list(self._index.values())[0]
 188 
 189   def _as_graph_element(self):
 190     obj = self.get()
 191     # pylint: disable=protected-access
 192     conv_fn = getattr(obj, "_as_graph_element", None)
 193     if conv_fn and callable(conv_fn):
 194       return conv_fn()
 195     return obj
 196 
 197 
 198 def _assign_on_device(device, variable, tensor):
 199   with ops.device(device):
 200     return variable.assign(array_ops.identity(tensor))

 203 DistributedVarOp = collections.namedtuple(
 204     "DistributedVarOp", ["name", "graph", "type"])

 207 class DistributedVariable(DistributedDelegate):
 208   """Holds a map from device to variables."""
 209   # TODO(josh11b): Support changing the set of variables if e.g. if new
 210   # devices are joining or a device is to leave.
 211 
 212   def __init__(self, index):
 213     # Child class must set self._primary_var before calling
 214     # super(...).__init__(index).
 215     self._common_name = self._primary_var.name.split(":")[0]
 216     # Use a weakref to make it easy to map from the contained values
 217     # to the container without introducing a reference cycle.
 218     for v in six.itervalues(index):
 219       v._distributed_container = weakref.ref(self)  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 220     # tf.keras keeps track of variables initialized using this attribute. When
 221     # tf.keras gets the default session, it initializes all uninitialized vars.
 222     # We need to make _keras_initialized a member of DistributedVariable because
 223     # without this it will use `__getattr__` which will delegate to a component
 224     # variable.
 225     self._keras_initialized = False
 226     # Typically, a `DistributedVariable`'s initializer is composed of the
 227     # initializers of the components variables. However, in some cases, such as
 228     # when restoring from a checkpoint, we may set the _initializer_op
 229     # property on the entire `DistributedVariable`.
 230     self._initializer_op = None
 231     super(DistributedVariable, self).__init__(index)
 232 
 233   def is_initialized(self, name=None):
 234     """Identifies if all the component variables are initialized.
 235 
 236     Args:
 237       name: Name of the final `logical_and` op.
 238 
 239     Returns:
 240       The op that evaluates to True or False depending on if all the
 241       component variables are initialized.
 242     """
 243     # We have to cast the self._index.values() to a `list` because when we
 244     # use `model_to_estimator` to run tf.keras models, self._index.values() is
 245     # of type `dict_values` and not `list`.
 246     values_list = list(self._index.values())
 247     result = values_list[0].is_initialized()
 248     # We iterate through the list of values except the last one to allow us to
 249     # name the final `logical_and` op the same name that is passed by the user
 250     # to the `is_initialized` op. For distributed variables, the
 251     # `is_initialized` op is a `logical_and` op.
 252     for v in values_list[1:-1]:
 253       result = math_ops.logical_and(result, v.is_initialized())
 254     result = math_ops.logical_and(result, values_list[-1].is_initialized(),
 255                                   name=name)
 256     return result
 257 
 258   @property
 259   def initializer(self):
 260     if self._initializer_op:
 261       init_op = self._initializer_op
 262     else:
 263       # return grouped ops of all the var initializations of component values of
 264       # the mirrored variable
 265       init_op = control_flow_ops.group(
 266           [v.initializer for v in self._index.values()])
 267     return init_op
 268 
 269   @property
 270   def graph(self):
 271     return self._primary_var.graph
 272 
 273   @property
 274   def _shared_name(self):
 275     return self._common_name
 276 
 277   @property
 278   def _unique_id(self):
 279     return self._primary_var._unique_id   # pylint: disable=protected-access
 280 
 281   @property
 282   def name(self):
 283     return self._primary_var.name
 284 
 285   @property
 286   def dtype(self):
 287     return self._primary_var.dtype
 288 
 289   @property
 290   def shape(self):
 291     return self._primary_var.shape
 292 
 293   def get_shape(self):
 294     return self._primary_var.get_shape()
 295 
 296   def to_proto(self, export_scope=None):
 297     return self._primary_var.to_proto(export_scope=export_scope)
 298 
 299   @property
 300   def op(self):
 301     # We want cross-tower code that does some var.op.X calls
 302     # to work (even if the current device isn't in self.devices), but
 303     # other uses of var.op in a cross-tower context to fail.
 304     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
 305       return DistributedVarOp(self._primary_var.op.name,
 306                               self._primary_var.op.graph,
 307                               self._primary_var.op.type)
 308     return self.get().op
 309 
 310   @property
 311   def _in_graph_mode(self):
 312     return self._primary_var._in_graph_mode   # pylint: disable=protected-access
 313 
 314   def read_value(self):
 315     return distribution_strategy_context.get_distribution_strategy().read_var(
 316         self)
 317 
 318   def _should_act_as_resource_variable(self):
 319     """Pass resource_variable_ops.is_resource_variable check."""
 320     pass

 326 class _MirroredSaveable(saver.BaseSaverBuilder.ResourceVariableSaveable):
 327   """Class for defining how to restore a MirroredVariable."""
 328 
 329   def __init__(self, mirrored_variable, primary_variable, name):
 330     self._mirrored_variable = mirrored_variable
 331     super(_MirroredSaveable, self).__init__(primary_variable, "", name)
 332 
 333   def restore(self, restored_tensors, restored_shapes):
 334     """Restore the same value into all variables."""
 335     tensor, = restored_tensors
 336     return control_flow_ops.group([
 337         _assign_on_device(d, v, tensor)
 338         for d, v in six.iteritems(self._mirrored_variable._index)])  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 339 
 340 
 341 class MirroredVariable(DistributedVariable, Mirrored,
 342                        checkpointable.CheckpointableBase):
 343   """Holds a map from device to variables whose values are kept in sync."""
 344 
 345   def __init__(self, index, primary_var, aggregation):
 346     self._primary_var = primary_var
 347     self._aggregation = aggregation
 348     super(MirroredVariable, self).__init__(index)
 349 
 350   # The arguments to update() are automatically unwrapped so the update()
 351   # function would normally see regular variables, not MirroredVariables.
 352   # However, the update function can still operate on wrapped MirroredVariables
 353   # through object members, captured arguments, etc. This is more likely in an
 354   # update_non_slot() function (like OptimizerV2._finish), which can
 355   # update several non-slot variables in one call.
 356   def _assign_func(self, *args, **kwargs):
 357     f = kwargs.pop("f")
 358     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
 359       update_device = distribute_lib.get_update_device()
 360       if update_device is not None:
 361         # We are calling an assign function on the mirrored variable in an
 362         # update context.
 363         v = self.get(device=update_device)
 364         return f(v, *args, **kwargs)
 365 
 366       # We are calling assign on the mirrored variable in cross tower context,
 367       # use update to update the variable.
 368       strategy = distribution_strategy_context.get_distribution_strategy()
 369       return strategy.update(self, f, *args, **kwargs)
 370     else:
 371       _assert_tower_context()
 372       # We are calling an assign function on the mirrored variable in tower
 373       # context.
 374       # We reduce the value we want to assign/add/sub. More details about how we
 375       # handle the different use cases can be found in the _reduce method.
 376       # We call the function on each of the mirrored variables with the reduced
 377       # value.
 378       if self._aggregation == vs.VariableAggregation.NONE:
 379         raise ValueError("You must specify an aggregation method to update a "
 380                          "MirroredVariable in Tower Context.")
 381 
 382       def merge_fn(strategy, value, *other_args, **other_kwargs):
 383         return strategy.update(
 384             self, f,
 385             strategy.reduce(
 386                 aggregation=self._aggregation, value=value, destinations=self),
 387             *other_args, **other_kwargs)
 388 
 389       return distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context().merge_call(
 390           merge_fn, *args, **kwargs)
 391 
 392   def assign_sub(self, *args, **kwargs):
 393     assign_sub_fn = lambda var, *a, **kw: var.assign_sub(*a, **kw)
 394     return self._assign_func(f=assign_sub_fn, *args, **kwargs)
 395 
 396   def assign_add(self, *args, **kwargs):
 397     assign_add_fn = lambda var, *a, **kw: var.assign_add(*a, **kw)
 398     return self._assign_func(f=assign_add_fn, *args, **kwargs)
 399 
 400   def assign(self, *args, **kwargs):
 401     assign_fn = lambda var, *a, **kw: var.assign(*a, **kw)
 402     return self._assign_func(f=assign_fn, *args, **kwargs)
 403 
 404   @property
 405   def aggregation(self):
 406     return self._aggregation
 407 
 408   def _get_cross_tower(self):
 409     device = device_util.canonicalize(device_util.current())
 410     if device in self._index:
 411       return array_ops.identity(self._index[device])
 412     return array_ops.identity(self._primary_var)
 413 
 414   def _as_graph_element(self):
 415     # pylint: disable=protected-access
 416     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
 417       return self._primary_var._as_graph_element()
 418     return self.get()._as_graph_element()
 419 
 420   def _gather_saveables_for_checkpoint(self):
 421     """Overrides CheckpointableBase method.
 422 
 423     This allows both name-based and object-based save and restore of
 424     MirroredVariables.
 425 
 426     Returns:
 427       A dictionary mapping attribute names to `SaveableObject` factories.
 428     """
 429     def _saveable_factory(name=self._common_name):
 430       return _MirroredSaveable(self, self._primary_var, name)
 431     return {checkpointable.VARIABLE_VALUE_KEY: _saveable_factory}
 432 
 433 
 434 # Register a conversion function which reads the value of the variable,
 435 # allowing instances of the class to be used as tensors.
 436 def _tensor_conversion_mirrored(var, dtype=None, name=None, as_ref=False):
 437   # Try to avoid assignments to and other mutations of MirroredVariable
 438   # state except through a DistributionStrategy.update() call.
 439   assert not as_ref
 440   return ops.internal_convert_to_tensor(
 441       var.get(), dtype=dtype, name=name, as_ref=as_ref)
 442 
 443 
 444 ops.register_tensor_conversion_function(MirroredVariable,
 445                                         _tensor_conversion_mirrored)

 448 def _enclosing_tpu_context():
 449   # pylint: disable=protected-access
 450   tpu_context = ops.get_default_graph()._get_control_flow_context()
 451   # pylint: enable=protected-access
 452   while tpu_context is not None and not isinstance(
 453       tpu_context, control_flow_ops.XLAControlFlowContext):
 454     tpu_context = tpu_context.outer_context
 455   return tpu_context

 458 # TODO(jhseu): Deduplicate code. We copy code because we don't want to
 459 # inherit from DistributedDelegate. DistributedDelegate will not work in a
 460 # tpu.replicate() because it assumes that you're in a device context where you
 461 # can operate on a single version of the variable, but a tpu.replicate()
 462 # operates on all variables and is replicated during a rewrite pass.
 463 class TPUMirroredVariable(checkpointable.CheckpointableBase):
 464   """Holds a map from device to TPU variables whose values are kept in sync."""
 465 
 466   def __init__(self, index, primary_var, aggregation):
 467     # Use a weakref to make it easy to map from the contained values
 468     # to the container without introducing a reference cycle.
 469     for v in six.itervalues(index):
 470       v._mirrored_container = weakref.ref(self)  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 471     self._index = {device_util.canonicalize(key): value
 472                    for key, value in six.iteritems(index)}
 473     self._primary_var = primary_var
 474     self._common_name = self._primary_var.name.split(":")[0]
 475     self._aggregation = aggregation
 476     # Needed for GradientTape
 477     self._trainable = self._primary_var.trainable
 478     # Typically like `DistributedVariable`, a `TPUMirroredVariable`'s
 479     # initializer is composed of the initializers of the components variables.
 480     # However, in some cases, such as when restoring from a checkpoint, we may
 481     # set the _initializer_op property on the entire `TPUMirroredVariable`.
 482     self._initializer_op = None
 483 
 484   def _get(self, device=None):
 485     """Returns the value for the current device or raises a ValueError."""
 486     if device is None:
 487       tower_context = distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context()
 488       if tower_context:
 489         device = tower_context.device
 490       else:
 491         device = distribute_lib.get_update_device()
 492         if device is None:
 493           return self._get_cross_tower()
 494     device = device_util.canonicalize(device)
 495     try:
 496       return self._index[device]
 497     except KeyError as e:
 498       six.raise_from(
 499           ValueError("Device %s not found in %s (current device %s)" %
 500                      (device, self._index.keys(), device_util.current())), e)
 501 
 502   # pylint: disable=multiple-statements
 503   def __add__(self, o): return self.read_value() + o
 504   def __radd__(self, o): return o + self.read_value()
 505   def __sub__(self, o): return self.read_value() - o
 506   def __rsub__(self, o): return o - self.read_value()
 507   def __mul__(self, o): return self.read_value() * o
 508   def __rmul__(self, o): return o * self.read_value()
 509   def __truediv__(self, o): return self.read_value() / o
 510   def __rtruediv__(self, o): return o / self.read_value()
 511   def __floordiv__(self, o): return self.read_value() // o
 512   def __rfloordiv__(self, o): return o // self.read_value()
 513   def __mod__(self, o): return self.read_value() % o
 514   def __rmod__(self, o): return o % self.read_value()
 515   def __lt__(self, o): return self.read_value() < o
 516   def __le__(self, o): return self.read_value() <= o
 517   def __gt__(self, o): return self.read_value() > o
 518   def __ge__(self, o): return self.read_value() >= o
 519   def __and__(self, o): return self.read_value() & o
 520   def __rand__(self, o): return o & self.read_value()
 521   def __or__(self, o): return self.read_value() | o
 522   def __ror__(self, o): return o | self.read_value()
 523   def __xor__(self, o): return self.read_value() ^ o
 524   def __rxor__(self, o): return o ^ self.read_value()
 525   def __getitem__(self, o): return self.read_value()[o]
 526   def __pow__(self, o, modulo=None): return pow(self.read_value(), o, modulo)
 527   def __rpow__(self, o): return pow(o, self.read_value())
 528   def __invert__(self): return ~self.read_value()
 529   def __neg__(self): return -self.read_value()
 530   def __abs__(self): return abs(self.read_value())
 531 
 532   def __div__(self, o):
 533     try:
 534       return self.read_value().__div__(o)
 535     except AttributeError:
 536       # See https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
 537       return NotImplemented
 538 
 539   def __rdiv__(self, o):
 540     try:
 541       return self.read_value().__rdiv__(o)
 542     except AttributeError:
 543       # See https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
 544       return NotImplemented
 545 
 546   def __matmul__(self, o):
 547     try:
 548       return self.read_value().__matmul__(o)
 549     except AttributeError:
 550       # See https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
 551       return NotImplemented

 554     try:

 556     except AttributeError:
 557       # See https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
 558       return NotImplemented

 560   @property
 561   def handle(self):
 562     # If we're in a tpu.rewrite(), return the replicated handle.
 563     tpu_context = _enclosing_tpu_context()
 564     if tpu_context is not None:
 565       return tpu_context.get_replicated_var_handle(
 566           self._common_name, nest.flatten(self._index))
 567 
 568     device = distribute_lib.get_update_device()
 569     if device is None:
 570       return self._primary_var.handle
 571     device = device_util.canonicalize(device)
 572     try:
 573       return self._index[device].handle
 574     except KeyError as e:
 575       six.raise_from(
 576           ValueError("Device %s not found in %s (current device %s)" %
 577                      (device, self._index.keys(), device_util.current())), e)
 578 
 579   @property
 580   def device(self):
 581     return self._get().device
 582 
 583   # The arguments to update() are automatically unwrapped so the update()
 584   # function would normally see regular variables, not MirroredVariables.
 585   # However, the update function can still operate on wrapped MirroredVariables
 586   # through object members, captured arguments, etc. This is more likely in an
 587   # update_non_slot() function (like OptimizerV2._finish), which can
 588   # update several non-slot variables in one call.
 589   def _assign_func(self, *args, **kwargs):
 590     if distribution_strategy_context.get_distribution_strategy().__class__.__name__ != "TPUStrategy":
 591       raise ValueError("You may only assign to a TPUMirroredVariable within a "
 592                        "TPUStrategy.")
 593     f = kwargs.pop("f")
 594     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
 595       if _enclosing_tpu_context() is not None:
 596         return distribution_strategy_context.get_distribution_strategy().update(
 597             self, f, *args, **kwargs)
 598 
 599       update_device = distribute_lib.get_update_device()
 600       # We are calling update on the mirrored variable in cross tower context.
 601       if update_device is not None:
 602         # We are calling an assign function on the mirrored variable in cross
 603         # tower context.
 604         v = self._get(device=update_device)
 605         return f(v, *args, **kwargs)
 606 
 607       return distribution_strategy_context.get_distribution_strategy().update(
 608           self, f, *args, **kwargs)
 609     else:
 610       _assert_tower_context()
 611       # We are calling an assign function on the mirrored variable in tower
 612       # context.
 613       # We reduce the value we want to assign/add/sub. More details about how we
 614       # handle the different use cases can be found in the _reduce method.
 615       # We call the function on each of the mirrored variables with the reduced
 616       # value.
 617       if self._aggregation == vs.VariableAggregation.NONE:
 618         raise ValueError("You must specify an aggregation method to update a "
 619                          "TPUMirroredVariable in Tower Context.")
 620 
 621       def merge_fn(strategy, value, *other_args, **other_kwargs):
 622         return strategy.update(
 623             self, f,
 624             strategy.reduce(
 625                 aggregation=self._aggregation, value=value, destinations=self),
 626             *other_args, **other_kwargs)
 627 
 628       return distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context().merge_call(
 629           merge_fn, *args, **kwargs)
 630 
 631   @contextlib.contextmanager
 632   def _handle_graph(self, handle):
 633     # Note: might have an eager tensor but not be executing eagerly when
 634     # building functions.
 635     if (context.executing_eagerly() or isinstance(handle, ops.EagerTensor)
 636         or ops.has_default_graph()):
 637       yield
 638     else:
 639       with handle.graph.as_default():
 640         yield
 641 
 642   @property
 643   def trainable(self):
 644     return self._trainable
 645 
 646   def _read_variable_op(self, parent_op=None):
 647     if self.trainable:
 648       tape.variable_accessed(self)
 649     if parent_op is not None:
 650       with ops.control_dependencies([parent_op]):
 651         return gen_resource_variable_ops.read_variable_op(
 652             self.handle, self.dtype)
 653 
 654     return gen_resource_variable_ops.read_variable_op(
 655         self.handle, self.dtype)
 656 
 657   def read_value(self):
 658     return self._read_variable_op()
 659 
 660   def assign_sub(self, *args, **kwargs):
 661     def assign_sub_fn(var, delta, **kw):
 662       name = kw.pop("name", None)
 663       read_value = kw.pop("read_value", True)
 664       with self._handle_graph(var.handle):
 665         op = gen_resource_variable_ops.assign_sub_variable_op(
 666             var.handle, ops.convert_to_tensor(delta, dtype=self.dtype),
 667             name=name)
 668       if read_value:
 669         return self._read_variable_op(parent_op=op)
 670       return op
 671 
 672     return self._assign_func(f=assign_sub_fn, *args, **kwargs)
 673 
 674   def assign_add(self, *args, **kwargs):
 675     def assign_add_fn(var, delta, **kw):
 676       name = kw.pop("name", None)
 677       read_value = kw.pop("read_value", True)
 678       with self._handle_graph(var.handle):
 679         op = gen_resource_variable_ops.assign_add_variable_op(
 680             var.handle, ops.convert_to_tensor(delta, dtype=self.dtype),
 681             name=name)
 682       if read_value:
 683         return self._read_variable_op(parent_op=op)
 684       return op
 685 
 686     return self._assign_func(f=assign_add_fn, *args, **kwargs)
 687 
 688   def assign(self, *args, **kwargs):
 689     def assign_fn(var, value, **kw):
 690       name = kw.pop("name", None)
 691       read_value = kw.pop("read_value", True)
 692       with self._handle_graph(var.handle):
 693         op = gen_resource_variable_ops.assign_variable_op(
 694             var.handle, ops.convert_to_tensor(value, dtype=self.dtype),
 695             name=name)
 696       if read_value:
 697         return self._read_variable_op(parent_op=op)
 698       return op
 699 
 700     return self._assign_func(f=assign_fn, *args, **kwargs)

 787   def _dense_var_to_tensor(self, dtype=None, name=None, as_ref=False):
 788     """Converts a variable to a tensor."""
 789     # pylint: disable=protected-access
 790     if _enclosing_tpu_context() is None:
 791       return self._get()._dense_var_to_tensor(dtype, name, as_ref)
 792     # pylint: enable=protected-access
 793     if dtype is not None and dtype != self.dtype:
 794       raise NotImplementedError
 795     if as_ref:
 796       return self.handle
 797     else:
 798       return self.read_value()

 800   def is_initialized(self, name=None):
 801     """Identifies if all the component variables are initialized.
 802 
 803     Args:
 804       name: Name of the final `logical_and` op.
 805 
 806     Returns:
 807       The op that evaluates to True or False depending on if all the
 808       component variables are initialized.
 809     """
 810     # TODO(jhseu): Do we need TPU context implementation?
 811 
 812     # We have to cast the self._index.values() to a `list` because when we
 813     # use `model_to_estimator` to run tf.keras models, self._index.values() is
 814     # of type `dict_values` and not `list`.
 815     values_list = nest.flatten(self._index)
 816     result = values_list[0].is_initialized()
 817     # We iterate through the list of values except the last one to allow us to
 818     # name the final `logical_and` op the same name that is passed by the user
 819     # to the `is_initialized` op. For distributed variables, the
 820     # `is_initialized` op is a `logical_and` op.
 821     for v in values_list[1:-1]:
 822       result = math_ops.logical_and(result, v.is_initialized())
 823     result = math_ops.logical_and(result, values_list[-1].is_initialized(),
 824                                   name=name)
 825     return result

 830 def _tensor_conversion_tpu_mirrored(var, dtype=None, name=None, as_ref=False):
 831   return var._dense_var_to_tensor(dtype=dtype, name=name, as_ref=as_ref)  # pylint: disable=protected-access

 834 ops.register_tensor_conversion_function(TPUMirroredVariable,
 835                                         _tensor_conversion_tpu_mirrored)
 836 ops.register_dense_tensor_like_type(TPUMirroredVariable)

 839 class _TowerLocalSaveable(saver.BaseSaverBuilder.SaveableObject):
 840   """Class for defining how to restore a TowerLocalVariable."""
 841 
 842   def __init__(self, tower_local_variable, name):
 843     self._tower_local_variable = tower_local_variable
 844     # We use a callable so that we don't have to evaluate this expression
 845     # in the case where we are trying to restore instead of save.
 846     def tensor():
 847       return distribution_strategy_context.get_distribution_strategy().read_var(
 848           tower_local_variable)
 849     spec = saver.BaseSaverBuilder.SaveSpec(
 850         tensor=tensor,
 851         slice_spec="",
 852         name=name,
 853         dtype=tower_local_variable.dtype)
 854     super(_TowerLocalSaveable, self).__init__(tensor, [spec], name)
 855 
 856   def restore(self, restored_tensors, restored_shapes):
 857     """Restore the same value into all variables."""
 858     tensor, = restored_tensors
 859     return self._tower_local_variable.assign(tensor)

 862 def _assert_tower_context():
 863   if not distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context():
 864     raise RuntimeError(
 865         "Tower-local variables may only be assigned in a tower context.")
 866 
 867 
 868 class TowerLocalVariable(DistributedVariable, PerDevice,
 869                          checkpointable.CheckpointableBase):
 870   """Holds a map from device to variables whose values are reduced on save."""
 871 
 872   def __init__(self, index, primary_var, aggregation):
 873     self._primary_var = primary_var
 874     self._aggregation = aggregation
 875     super(TowerLocalVariable, self).__init__(index)
 876 
 877   def assign_sub(self, *args, **kwargs):
 878     _assert_tower_context()
 879     return self.get().assign_sub(*args, **kwargs)
 880 
 881   def assign_add(self, *args, **kwargs):
 882     _assert_tower_context()
 883     return self.get().assign_add(*args, **kwargs)
 884 
 885   def assign(self, *args, **kwargs):
 886     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
 887       # To preserve the sum across save and restore, we have to divide the
 888       # total across all devices when restoring a variable that was summed
 889       # when saving.
 890       tensor = args[0]
 891       if self._aggregation == vs.VariableAggregation.SUM:
 892         tensor *= 1. / len(self.devices)
 893       return control_flow_ops.group(
 894           [_assign_on_device(d, v, tensor)
 895            for d, v in six.iteritems(self._index)])
 896     else:
 897       _assert_tower_context()
 898       return self.get().assign(*args, **kwargs)
 899 
 900   @property
 901   def aggregation(self):
 902     return self._aggregation
 903 
 904   def _get_cross_tower(self):
 905     if self._aggregation == vs.VariableAggregation.ONLY_FIRST_TOWER:
 906       return self._primary_var
 907     all_components = tuple(self._index.values())
 908     # TODO(josh11b): Use a strategy-specific method.
 909     total = math_ops.add_n(all_components)
 910     if self._aggregation == vs.VariableAggregation.MEAN:
 911       return total * (1./ len(all_components))
 912     return total
 913 
 914   def _as_graph_element(self):
 915     # pylint: disable=protected-access
 916     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
 917       return self._get_cross_tower()
 918     return self.get()._as_graph_element()
 919 
 920   def _gather_saveables_for_checkpoint(self):
 921     """Overrides CheckpointableBase method.
 922 
 923     This allows both name-based and object-based save and restore of
 924     TowerLocalVariables.
 925 
 926     Returns:
 927       A dictionary mapping attribute names to `SaveableObject` factories.
 928     """
 929     def _saveable_factory(name=self._common_name):
 930       return _TowerLocalSaveable(self, name)
 931     return {checkpointable.VARIABLE_VALUE_KEY: _saveable_factory}

 945 def _devices_match(d1, d2):
 946   return device_util.canonicalize(d1) == device_util.canonicalize(d2)

 949 def regroup(per_device, wrap_class=PerDevice):
 950   """Makes device->nest map into a nest of PerDevice/Mirrored values."""
 951   items = list(per_device.items())
 952   assert items
 953   v0 = items[0][1]  # First value
 954 
 955   if isinstance(v0, list):
 956     for _, v in items[1:]:
 957       assert isinstance(v, list)
 958       assert len(v) == len(v0), ("len(v) == %d, len(v0) == %d, v: %s, v0: %s" %
 959                                  (len(v), len(v0), v, v0))
 960     return [regroup({k: v[i] for k, v in items}, wrap_class)
 961             for i in range(len(v0))]
 962 
 963   if isinstance(v0, tuple):
 964     for _, v in items[1:]:
 965       assert isinstance(v, tuple)
 966       assert len(v) == len(v0)
 967     regrouped_tuple = tuple(regroup({k: v[i] for k, v in items}, wrap_class)
 968                             for i in range(len(v0)))
 969     if hasattr(v0, "_fields"):
 970       # This tuple is in fact a namedtuple! Create a new namedtuple instance
 971       # and initialize it with the regrouped values:
 972       assert hasattr(type(v0), "_make")
 973       return type(v0)._make(regrouped_tuple)
 974     else:
 975       return regrouped_tuple
 976 
 977   if isinstance(v0, dict):
 978     v0keys = set(v0.keys())
 979     for _, v in items[1:]:
 980       assert isinstance(v, dict)
 981       assert set(v.keys()) == v0keys
 982     return {key: regroup({k: v[key] for k, v in items}, wrap_class)
 983             for key in v0keys}
 984 
 985   # If exactly the same object across all devices, return it unwrapped.
 986   same_id = True
 987   for _, v in items[1:]:
 988     if v is not v0:
 989       same_id = False
 990       break
 991   # Consider three cases where same_id is true:
 992   # * If v0 is a DistributedVariable (a MirroredVariable or
 993   #   TowerLocalVariable, and same_id means it is the same across all
 994   #   devices), we want to return it. We check DistributedVariable
 995   #   specifically since it can look like it has a
 996   #   _distributed_container member since its members do.
 997   # * If v0 is a member of a distributed variable, in which case
 998   #   hasattr(v0, "_distributed_container") is true, we want to
 999   #   return the DistributedVariable that contains it using the
1000   #   _distributed_container logic below. This case can trigger
1001   #   same_id when there is only one device.
1002   # * In any other situation, same_id means we return v0.
1003   if same_id and (isinstance(v0, DistributedVariable) or
1004                   not hasattr(v0, "_distributed_container")):
1005     return v0
1006 
1007   # Detect the case where each device has a parallel component of the
1008   # same MirroredVariable (or TowerLocalVariable). In this case we
1009   # want to return the containing MirroredVariable, after a bunch of
1010   # sanity checking. In particular, each component should have the
1011   # same container, and the devices of the variables should match the
1012   # keys of the per-device dictionary.
1013   if hasattr(v0, "_distributed_container"):
1014     # pylint: disable=protected-access
1015     assert not isinstance(v0, MirroredVariable), (
1016         "ids = %s, items = %s" % ([id(v[1]) for v in items], items))
1017     assert _devices_match(v0.device, items[0][0]), (
1018         "v0.device = %s, items = %s" % (v0.device, items))
1019     distributed_container = v0._distributed_container()
1020     assert distributed_container is not None
1021     for d, v in items[1:]:
1022       assert _devices_match(v.device, d), (
1023           "v.device = %s, d = %s, items = %s" % (v.device, d, items))
1024       assert distributed_container is v._distributed_container()
1025     return distributed_container
1026   # pylint: enable=protected-access
1027 
1028   return wrap_class(per_device)
1029

1031 def select_device(device, structured):
1032   """Specialize a nest of regular & per-device values for one device."""
1033   def _get(x):
1034     return x.get(device) if isinstance(x, DistributedValues) else x
1035 
1036   return nest.map_structure(_get, structured)

1039 def select_device_mirrored(device, structured):
1040   """Specialize a nest of regular & mirrored values for one device."""
1041   def _get_mirrored(x):
1042     if isinstance(x, DistributedValues):
1043       if not isinstance(x, Mirrored):
1044         raise TypeError(
1045             "Expected value to be mirrored across towers: %s in %s." %
1046             (x, structured))
1047       return x.get(device)
1048     else:
1049       return x
1050 
1051   return nest.map_structure(_get_mirrored, structured)
1052 
1053 
1054 def update_regroup(strategy, updates, should_group):
1055   """Regroup for an update, with dependencies to ensure all updates execute."""
1056   regrouped = regroup(updates, Mirrored)
1057   if not should_group:
1058     return nest.map_structure(strategy.unwrap, regrouped)
1059   grouped_flat = []
1060   for u in nest.flatten(regrouped):
1061     if isinstance(u, DistributedValues):
1062       g = strategy.group(u)
1063       if u.is_tensor_like:
1064         # Make sure we run all updates. Without this, something like
1065         # session.run(strategy.update(...)) may only update one tower.
1066         index = {}
1067         for d in u.devices:
1068           with ops.device(d), ops.control_dependencies([g]):
1069             index[d] = array_ops.identity(u.get(d))
1070         g = Mirrored(index)
1071     else:
1072       g = u
1073     grouped_flat.append(g)
1074   return nest.pack_sequence_as(regrouped, grouped_flat)
1075 
1076 
1077 class PerDeviceDataIterator(object):
1078   """An iterator (like `tf.data.Iterator`) into a `PerDeviceDataset`."""
1079 
1080   def __init__(self, iterator, devices, prefetch_on_device=None):
1081     self._iterator = iterator
1082     self._devices = devices
1083     self._prefetch_on_device = prefetch_on_device
1084 
1085   @property
1086   def initializer(self):
1087     return self._iterator.initializer
1088 
1089   def get_next(self, name=None):
1090     """Scatter the input across devices."""
1091     if self._prefetch_on_device:
1092       data_list = self._iterator.get_next(name=name)
1093       index = dict(zip(self._devices, data_list))
1094     else:
1095       batch = self._iterator.get_next(name=name)
1096       index = {}
1097       def get_ith(i):
1098         return lambda x: x[i]
1099 
1100       for i, d in enumerate(self._devices):
1101         index[d] = nest.map_structure(get_ith(i), batch)
1102         if context.executing_eagerly():
1103           with ops.device(d):
1104             index[d] = nest.map_structure(array_ops.identity, index[d])
1105 
1106     return regroup(index)
1107

1109 class PerDeviceDataset(object):
1110   """Like `tf.data.Dataset` split devices, producing `PerDevice` data."""
1111 
1112   def __init__(self, dataset, devices, prefetch_on_device=None):
1113     self._devices = devices
1114 
1115     # Default to using prefetching in graph mode, unless specified.
1116     # TODO(priyag): Enable prefetching in eager mode.
1117     self._prefetch_on_device = prefetch_on_device
1118     if self._prefetch_on_device is None:
1119       self._prefetch_on_device = not context.executing_eagerly()
1120     assert not (self._prefetch_on_device and context.executing_eagerly()), (
1121         "Prefetching is only supported in graph mode currently")
1122 
1123     if self._prefetch_on_device:
1124       self._dataset = dataset.apply(
1125           prefetching_ops_v2.prefetch_to_devices(self._devices))
1126     else:
1127       # TODO(priyag): If dropping remainder is not appropriate, find another
1128       # approach to distributing the dataset when not possible to divide evenly.
1129       # Possibly not an issue when we start using PartitionedDataset.
1130       self._dataset = dataset.batch(len(devices), drop_remainder=True)
1131 
1132   def make_one_shot_iterator(self):
1133     """Get a one time use iterator for the distributed PerDeviceDataset."""
1134     dataset_iterator = self._dataset.make_one_shot_iterator()
1135     return PerDeviceDataIterator(dataset_iterator, self._devices,
1136                                  self._prefetch_on_device)
1137 
1138   def make_initializable_iterator(self):
1139     """Get an initializable iterator for the distributed PerDeviceDataset."""
1140     dataset_iterator = self._dataset.make_initializable_iterator()
1141     return PerDeviceDataIterator(dataset_iterator, self._devices,
1142                                  self._prefetch_on_device)

1145 class MultiWorkerDataIterator(object):
1146   """An iterator (like `tf.data.Iterator`) into a `MultiWorkerDataset`."""
1147 
1148   def __init__(self, iterators, worker_device_map):
1149     """Initialize the MultiWorkerDataIterator object.
1150 
1151     Args:
1152       iterators: a dict mapping from each worker to an iterator for
1153         that worker.
1154       worker_device_map: a dict mapping from each worker's devices to a list of
1155         devices that belong to this worker.
1156 
1157     Raises:
1158       ValueError: if iterators and worker_device_map are not compatible.
1159     """
1160     self._iterators = iterators
1161     self._worker_device_map = worker_device_map
1162     if set(self._iterators) != set(self._worker_device_map):
1163       raise ValueError("iterators and worker_device_map are not compatible.")
1164 
1165   @property
1166   def initializer(self):
1167     return control_flow_ops.group(
1168         [iterator.initializer for iterator in self._iterators.values()])
1169 
1170   def get_next(self, name=None):
1171     """Scatter the input across hosts and devices."""
1172     index = {}
1173     for worker, iterator in six.iteritems(self._iterators):
1174       if name is not None:
1175         d = tf_device.DeviceSpec.from_string(worker)
1176         new_name = "%s_%s_%d" % (name, d.job, d.task)
1177       else:
1178         new_name = None
1179       with ops.device(worker):
1180         data_per_worker = iterator.get_next(name=new_name)
1181 
1182       worker_devices = self._worker_device_map[worker]
1183       # Ungroup these per-device value so as to get a flat map from devices to
1184       # values.
1185       for d in worker_devices:
1186         v = select_device(d, data_per_worker)
1187         if d in index:
1188           raise ValueError("Duplicated devices in worker_device_map: %r" % v)
1189         index[d] = v
1190 
1191     return regroup(index)
1192

1194 class MultiWorkerDataset(object):
1195   """Like a `tf.data.Dataset` that distributes data to different workers.
1196 
1197   Each worker gets one shard of the input dataset. It is currently not working
1198   in
1199   eager mode.
1200   """
1201 
1202   def __init__(self, dataset_fn, worker_device_map, prefetch_on_device=None,
1203                auto_shard=False):
1204     """Initialize the MultiWorkerDataset object.
1205 
1206     Args:
1207       dataset_fn: a function that returns a `tf.data.Dataset`.
1208       worker_device_map: a dict mapping from each worker to a list of devices
1209         that belong to this worker.
1210       prefetch_on_device: whether to prefetch to devices.
1211       auto_shard: whether to auto-shard the dataset.
1212     """
1213     self._worker_device_map = worker_device_map
1214     self._datasets = {}
1215     # TODO(yuefengz, priyag): support different set of jobs for input
1216     # processing.
1217     for i, (worker, worker_devices) in enumerate(
1218         six.iteritems(worker_device_map)):
1219       with ops.device(worker):
1220         worker_input = dataset_fn()
1221         if auto_shard:
1222           worker_input = input_ops.auto_shard_dataset(
1223               worker_input, len(worker_device_map), i)
1224         self._datasets[worker] = PerDeviceDataset(
1225             worker_input, worker_devices, prefetch_on_device=prefetch_on_device)
1226 
1227   def make_one_shot_iterator(self):
1228     iterators = {}
1229     for worker, dataset in six.iteritems(self._datasets):
1230       with ops.device(worker):
1231         iterators[worker] = dataset.make_one_shot_iterator()
1232     return MultiWorkerDataIterator(iterators, self._worker_device_map)
1233 
1234   def make_initializable_iterator(self):
1235     iterators = {}
1236     for worker, dataset in six.iteritems(self._datasets):
1237       with ops.device(worker):
1238         iterators[worker] = dataset.make_initializable_iterator()
1239     return MultiWorkerDataIterator(iterators, self._worker_device_map)

1242 class _PerKey(object):
1243   """Holds data associated by keys."""

1256     return self._index[-1][-1].dtype

1259     return "%s:%s" % (self.__class__.__name__, self._index)

1266   """Holds input for multiple iterations at once."""

1270     super(PerIteration, self).__init__(*[batch._index for batch in index])

1277 class MultiIterator(object):
1278   """Iterator that returns results of multiple get_next()s."""
1279 
1280   def __init__(self, dataset_iterator, iterations, batches_per_iteration):
1281     self._dataset_iterator = dataset_iterator
1282     self._iterations = iterations
1283     self._batches_per_iteration = batches_per_iteration
1284 
1285   def get_next(self, name=None):
1286     """Return PerIteration with `iterations x batches_per_iteration` inputs."""
1287     data = []
1288     for _ in range(self._batches_per_iteration):
1289       batch = []
1290       for _ in range(self._iterations):
1291         batch.append(self._dataset_iterator.get_next(name=name))
1292       data.append(batch)
1293 
1294     # Here is an example.  Suppose each get_next returns a tuple of two tensors.
1295     # For 3 `iterations` and 2 `batches_per_iteration`, the `data` is:
1296     # [[(a,z), (b,y), (c,x)], [(A,Z), (B,Y), (C,X)]]
1297     #
1298     # After the first `map_structure` it gets transformed to:
1299     #  [(Batches(a, A), Batches(z, Z)),
1300     #   (Batches(b, B), Batches(y, Y)),
1301     #   (Batches(c, C), Batches(x, X))]
1302     #
1303     # After the second `map_structure` it gets transformed to a tuple of:
1304     # (PerIteration([Batches(a, A), Batches(b, B), Batches(c, C)]),
1305     #  PerIteration([Batches(z, Z), Batches(y, Y), Batches(x, X)]))
1306 
1307     data = nest.map_structure(Batches, *data)
1308     data = nest.map_structure(PerIteration, *data)
1309 
1310     return data
1311 
1312   @property
1313   def initializer(self):
1314     return self._dataset_iterator.initializer
1315 
1316 
1317 class PerIterationDataset(object):
1318   """A dataset that returns MultiIterators."""
1319 
1320   def __init__(self, dataset, iterations, batches_per_iteration):
1321     self._dataset = dataset
1322     self._iterations = iterations
1323     self._batches_per_iteration = batches_per_iteration
1324 
1325   def make_one_shot_iterator(self):
1326     iterator = self._dataset.make_one_shot_iterator()
1327     return MultiIterator(iterator, self._iterations,
1328                          self._batches_per_iteration)
1329 
1330   def make_initializable_iterator(self):
1331     iterator = self._dataset.make_initializable_iterator()
1332     return MultiIterator(iterator, self._iterations,
1333                          self._batches_per_iteration)

1346 class MultiStepContext(object):
1347   """A context object that can be used to capture things when running steps.
1348 
1349   This context object is useful when running multiple steps at a time using the
1350   `run_steps_on_dataset` API. For e.g. it allows the user's step function to
1351   specify which outputs to emit at what frequency. Currently it supports
1352   capturing output from the last step, as well as capturing non tensor outputs.
1353   In the future it will be augmented to support other use cases such as output
1354   each N steps.
1355   """
1356 
1357   def __init__(self):
1358     """Initializes an output context.
1359 
1360     Returns:
1361       A context object.
1362     """
1363     self._last_step_outputs = {}
1364     self._last_step_outputs_aggregations = {}
1365     self._non_tensor_outputs = {}
1366 
1367   @property
1368   def last_step_outputs(self):
1369     """A dictionary consisting of outputs to be captured on last step.
1370 
1371     Keys in the dictionary are names of tensors to be captured, as specified
1372     when `set_last_step_output` is called.
1373     Values in the dictionary are the tensors themselves. If
1374     `set_last_step_output` was called with an `aggregation` for this output,
1375     then the value is the aggregated value.
1376 
1377     Returns:
1378       A dictionary with last step outputs.
1379     """
1380     return self._last_step_outputs
1381 
1382   def _set_last_step_outputs(self, outputs):
1383     """Replace the entire dictionary of last step outputs."""
1384     if not isinstance(outputs, dict):
1385       raise ValueError("Need a dictionary to set last_step_outputs.")
1386     self._last_step_outputs = outputs
1387 
1388   def set_last_step_output(self, name, output,
1389                            aggregation=variables_lib.VariableAggregation.NONE):
1390     """Set `output` with `name` to be outputted from the last step.
1391 
1392     Args:
1393       name: String, name to identify the output. Doesn't need to match tensor
1394         name.
1395       output: The tensors that should be outputted with `name`. See below for
1396         actual types supported.
1397       aggregation: Aggregation method to use to aggregate outputs from multiple
1398         towers. Required if `set_last_step_output` is called in a tower context.
1399         Optional in cross_tower_context.
1400         When present, the outputs from all the towers are aggregated using the
1401         current distribution strategy's `reduce` method. Hence, the type of
1402         `output` must be what's supported by the corresponding `reduce` method.
1403         For e.g. if using MirroredStrategy and aggregation is set, output
1404         must be a `PerDevice` value.
1405         The aggregation method is also recorded in a dictionary
1406         `_last_step_outputs_aggregations` for later interpreting of the
1407         outputs as already reduced or not.
1408 
1409     """
1410     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
1411       self._last_step_outputs_aggregations[name] = aggregation
1412       if aggregation is variables_lib.VariableAggregation.NONE:
1413         self._last_step_outputs[name] = output
1414       else:
1415         distribution = distribution_strategy_context.get_distribution_strategy()
1416         self._last_step_outputs[name] = distribution.reduce(
1417             aggregation, output, destinations="/device:CPU:0")
1418     else:
1419       assert aggregation is not variables_lib.VariableAggregation.NONE
1420       def merge_fn(distribution, value):
1421         self._last_step_outputs[name] = distribution.reduce(
1422             aggregation, value, destinations="/device:CPU:0")
1423         # Setting this inside the `merge_fn` because all towers share the same
1424         # context object, so it's more robust to set it only once (even if all
1425         # the towers are trying to set the same value).
1426         self._last_step_outputs_aggregations[name] = aggregation
1427 
1428       distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context().merge_call(
1429           merge_fn, output)
1430 
1431   @property
1432   def non_tensor_outputs(self):
1433     """A dictionary consisting of any non tensor outputs to be captured."""
1434     return self._non_tensor_outputs
1435 
1436   def set_non_tensor_output(self, name, output):
1437     """Set `output` with `name` to be captured as a non tensor output."""
1438     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
1439       self._non_tensor_outputs[name] = output
1440     else:
1441       def merge_fn(distribution, value):
1442         # NOTE(priyag): For non tensor outputs, we simply return all the values
1443         # in a list as aggregation doesn't make sense on non tensors.
1444         self._non_tensor_outputs[name] = distribution.unwrap(value)
1445       distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context().merge_call(
1446           merge_fn, output)
1447 
1448 
1449 def value_container(val):
1450   """Returns the container that this per-device `value` belongs to.
1451 
1452   Args:
1453     val: A value returned by `call_for_each_tower()` or a variable
1454       created in `scope()`.
1455 
1456   Returns:
1457     A container that `value` belongs to.
1458     If value does not belong to any container (including the case of
1459     container having been destroyed), returns the value itself.
1460   """
1461   # pylint: disable=protected-access
1462   if (hasattr(val, "_distributed_container") and
1463       # DistributedVariable has _distributed_container defined
1464       # but we don't want to return it.
1465       not isinstance(val, DistributedVariable)):
1466     container = val._distributed_container()
1467     # pylint: disable=protected-access
1468     if container is not None:
1469       return container
1470   return val

1473 # TODO(josh11b): Descend from Variable.
1474 class AggregatingVariable(checkpointable.CheckpointableBase):
1475   """A wrapper around a variable that aggregates updates across towers."""
1476 
1477   def __init__(self, v, aggregation):
1478     self._v = v
1479     # TODO(josh11b): Set v._distributed_container?
1480     # v._distributed_container = weakref.ref(self)  # pylint: disable=protected-access
1481     self._aggregation = aggregation
1482 
1483   def get(self):
1484     return self._v
1485 
1486   def __getattr__(self, name):
1487     return getattr(self._v, name)
1488 
1489   def _assign_func(self, *args, **kwargs):
1490     f = kwargs.pop("f")
1491     if distribution_strategy_context.get_cross_tower_context():
1492       update_device = distribute_lib.get_update_device()
1493       if update_device is not None:
1494         # We are calling an assign function in an update context.
1495         return f(self._v, *args, **kwargs)
1496 
1497       # We are calling an assign function in cross tower context, wrap it in an
1498       # update call.
1499       return distribution_strategy_context.get_distribution_strategy().update(
1500           self, f, *args, **kwargs)
1501     else:
1502       assert distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context()
1503       # We are calling an assign function in tower context.
1504       # We reduce the value we want to assign/add/sub. More details about how we
1505       # handle the different use cases can be found in the _reduce method.
1506       # We call the function with the reduced value.
1507       if self._aggregation == vs.VariableAggregation.NONE:
1508         raise ValueError("You must specify an aggregation method to update a "
1509                          "a variable in Tower Context.")
1510 
1511       def merge_fn(strategy, value, *other_args, **other_kwargs):
1512         return strategy.update(
1513             self, f,
1514             strategy.reduce(
1515                 aggregation=self._aggregation, value=value, destinations=self),
1516             *other_args, **other_kwargs)
1517 
1518       return distribution_strategy_context.get_tower_context().merge_call(
1519           merge_fn, *args, **kwargs)
1520 
1521   def assign_sub(self, *args, **kwargs):
1522     assign_sub_fn = lambda var, *a, **kw: var.assign_sub(*a, **kw)
1523     return self._assign_func(f=assign_sub_fn, *args, **kwargs)
1524 
1525   def assign_add(self, *args, **kwargs):
1526     assign_add_fn = lambda var, *a, **kw: var.assign_add(*a, **kw)
1527     return self._assign_func(f=assign_add_fn, *args, **kwargs)
1528 
1529   def assign(self, *args, **kwargs):
1530     assign_fn = lambda var, *a, **kw: var.assign(*a, **kw)
1531     return self._assign_func(f=assign_fn, *args, **kwargs)
1532 
1533   @property
1534   def aggregation(self):
1535     return self._aggregation
1536 
1537   @property
1538   def name(self):
1539     return self._v.name
1540 
1541   @property
1542   def dtype(self):
1543     return self._v.dtype
1544 
1545   # TODO(josh11b): Test saving & restoring.
1546   def _gather_saveables_for_checkpoint(self):
1547     return {checkpointable.VARIABLE_VALUE_KEY: self._v}
1548 
1549   # pylint: disable=multiple-statements
1550   def __add__(self, o): return self._v + o
1551   def __radd__(self, o): return o + self._v
1552   def __sub__(self, o): return self._v - o
1553   def __rsub__(self, o): return o - self._v
1554   def __mul__(self, o): return self._v * o
1555   def __rmul__(self, o): return o * self._v
1556   def __truediv__(self, o): return self._v / o
1557   def __rtruediv__(self, o): return o / self._v
1558   def __floordiv__(self, o): return self._v // o
1559   def __rfloordiv__(self, o): return o // self._v
1560   def __mod__(self, o): return self._v % o
1561   def __rmod__(self, o): return o % self._v
1562   def __lt__(self, o): return self._v < o
1563   def __le__(self, o): return self._v <= o
1564   def __gt__(self, o): return self._v > o
1565   def __ge__(self, o): return self._v >= o
1566   def __and__(self, o): return self._v & o
1567   def __rand__(self, o): return o & self._v
1568   def __or__(self, o): return self._v | o
1569   def __ror__(self, o): return o | self._v
1570   def __xor__(self, o): return self._v ^ o
1571   def __rxor__(self, o): return o ^ self._v
1572   def __getitem__(self, o): return self._v[o]
1573   def __pow__(self, o, modulo=None): return pow(self._v, o, modulo)
1574   def __rpow__(self, o): return pow(o, self._v)
1575   def __invert__(self): return ~self._v
1576   def __neg__(self): return -self._v
1577   def __abs__(self): return abs(self._v)
1578 
1579   def __div__(self, o):
1580     try:
1581       return self._v.__div__(o)
1582     except AttributeError:

1584       return NotImplemented
